 The Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="How to become a trainer in a hospital - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-hmvnCu drWcAT pf-15_"/></div></div></div></div></div><div data-section-id="pf-30c8" data-category="Generic Content" data-name="Matcha" data-pf-type="Section" class="sc-cqJhZP gdQPUt pf-16_"><div style="--cw:1170px" class="sc-jefHZX kyAaUw"><div class="sc-iAKWXU lesjfG pf-17_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:0px;--s-sm:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-cTAIfT dQNWym pf-18_"><p class="sc-hAWBJg hGXVfC pf-19_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-fbWUsZ UDgXo pf-21_">Becoming a trainer in a hospital is a rewarding career path that allows healthcare professionals to contribute to developing competent teams and ensure high-quality care. This blog will explore why hospitals are regulated by the Care Quality Commission (CQC) and the significance of training in the hospital setting. We will also discuss the importance of Continuous Professional Development (CPD) training and how professionals can become trainers through the <a href="https://www.mandatorytraining.co.uk/pages/train-the-trainer-courses-and-qualifications" target="_blank"><i><span style="color: rgb(0, 102, 204);">train-the-trainer</span></i></a> model.</span></p><h2 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-jeraig eTNnJl pf-22_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-fbWUsZ UDgXo pf-24_">Why CQC regulates hospitals and values training</span></h2><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Why_CQC_regulates_hospitals_and_values_training_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg?v=1694011842" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Why_CQC_regulates_hospitals_and_values_training_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg?v=1694011842 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Why_CQC_regulates_hospitals_and_values_training_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK_500x.jpg?v=1694011842 320w" width="1820" height="1213" alt="Why CQC regulates hospitals and values training - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="Why CQC regulates hospitals and values training - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-hmvnCu drWcAT pf-25_"/><p class="sc-hAWBJg hGXVfC pf-26_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-fbWUsZ UDgXo pf-28_">The Care Quality Commission (CQC) regulates both NHS trusts and private hospitals to ensure they provide patients with high-quality, safe, and effective care. The CQC is responsible for monitoring, inspecting, and regulating all healthcare providers in the UK, including hospitals, to verify that they meet the required standards of care and patient safety outlined in the Health and Social Care Act 2008. They use a variety of tools, such as inspections, ratings, and enforcement actions, to establish that hospitals provide safe, effective, and compassionate care to patients.<br><br>CQC regulates hospitals in England to ensure that they have sufficient numbers of suitably qualified, competent, skilled, and experienced staff to meet people's care and treatment needs, as required by Regulation 18. They set standards for staffing levels and check that providers have effective systems in place to train their staff and maintain their skills. Staff training is included in the fundamental standards, which are the basic requirements that health and social care providers must meet to warrant high-quality care. <br> </span></p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-jeraig eTNnJl pf-29_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-fbWUsZ UDgXo pf-31_">The Importance of CPD training in hospitals </span></h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/The_Importance_of_CPD_training_in_hospitals_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg?v=1694011924" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/The_Importance_of_CPD_training_in_hospitals_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK.jpg?v=1694011924 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/The_Importance_of_CPD_training_in_hospitals_-_The_Mandatory_Training_Group_UK_500x.jpg?v=1694011924 320w" width="1784" height="1190" alt="The Importance of CPD training in hospitals - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" title="The Importance of CPD training in hospitals - The Mandatory Training Group UK -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-hmvnCu drWcAT pf-32_"/><p class="sc-hAWBJg hGXVfC pf-33_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-fbWUsZ UDgXo pf-35_">Continuing Professional Development (CPD) is essential for healthcare professionals, regardless of their position. It enables professionals, including doctors, nurses, dental staff, pharmacists, and allied health professionals, to stay up-to-date with the latest information and approaches in their field. It also allows them to progress in their careers and provide high-quality and safe patient care.<br><br>Engaging in CPD activities helps healthcare professionals enhance their skills and knowledge, maintain their professional competence, and build a strong professional reputation. Through CPD, professionals can stay informed about new developments in guidelines, legal obligations, innovation, and hospital standards. It also enables them to discover new specialisations and fields of practice that interest them and enhances their ability to provide individualised care to patients. Furthermore, CPD fosters a culture of lifelong learning and improvement among hospital workers. Continuous learning is essential in healthcare, as it enables professionals to adapt to new challenges, incorporate evidence-based practices, and deliver high-quality care. <br> </span></p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-jeraig eTNnJl pf-36_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-fbWUsZ UDgXo pf-38_">Training to develop competent teams</span></h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/